I have, over the past few years, had surprisingly=C2=A0many=C2=A0occasions =
to ponder the following question: If you had a magic lamp=C2=A0that allowed=
 you to move up the price of a liquid publicly traded stock arbitrarily,=C2=
=A0by a large amount, a handful of times, what would you do with it? There=
=E2=80=99s some stock that trades at $20, and you could rub the lamp and it=
 would go to $30 for like a day or two: What do you do?I think there is a t=
heoretically=C2=A0correct=C2=A0answer, though it is neither investing nor l=
egal nor magical=C2=A0advice. It goes like this:=09Spend all of your money =
on somewhat out-of-the-money short-dated call options on the stock.=09Rub t=
he lamp.=09Sell the options.This maximizes your leverage in the trade: Inst=
ead of paying $20 to buy the stock, you pay (say) $1 to buy out-of-the-mone=
y options struck at say $25. You rub the lamp, the stock jumps to $30, the =
options jump to (say) $6, and you sell them all. You=E2=80=99ve made a 500%=
 return using options=C2=A0instead of a 50% return by buying stock.There is=
 a legal nuance here, though I stress that nothing here is legal advice. Th=
e legal nuance is that, in the real world, there are no magic lamps. In the=
 real world, the way to actually move publicly traded stocks is mostly by m=
aking public statements to people who care about what you have to say (and =
