0;">But there are limits. Big banks that help fund the lending activities o=
f private credit firms typically cap the amount of such PIK deals they will=
 finance. Synthetic PIKs are a workaround to those constraints. =E2=80=A6</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a synthetic PIK, lenders provide a compan=
y two separate pieces of debt: the main loan the company planned to borrow =
in the first place, plus a smaller delayed-draw term loan that sits at the =
same level in the capital structure and has similar terms. Delayed-draw mea=
ns a borrower has access to the full amount of that loan when the deal clos=
es, but can choose to actually borrow the money at a later date.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When interest on the first loan needs to be paid, the=
 company taps the delayed-draw term loan. This allows the company to pay th=
e interest in cash, but it=E2=80=99s technically doing so through adding mo=
re debt to its balance sheet.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
I love it. Notice the=C2=A0<em>reason=C2=A0</em>for the synthetic PIK, as o=
pposed to a regular PIK.=C2=A0The private credit fund doesn=E2=80=99t care:=
 Paying interest in the form of more debt, or paying interest in cash while=
 simultaneously borrowing more, are exactly identical transactions as far a=
s its credit risk is concerned. What matters is that the private credit fun=
d has some contract with somebody else that says =E2=80=9Cwe promise not to=
 do too many PIK deals,=E2=80=9D and a synthetic PIK deal is not=C2=A0<em>t=
